##
## Chapter 1	General things
##

@Node PSAmiga "The PacShell for Amiga"
    PacShell is a program, that gives you an unified interface
    for different archviers and archive formats. It allows to
    handle this archives in an intuitive graphical environment.
    It was an important goal in development to unify the
    handling of the different archive formats as much as
    possible, so that you must only know how to do things like
    extracting with PacShell and not for every single archiver.
    The program I used as a reference is the PacShell for
    Atari ST, written by Holger Weets. Most of the archive
    reading algorithms are taken from there, for example. But
    there are also many differences.
    For me, it was very important to have the possibility to
    select files from more than one directory and to archive
    this with a single archiver-call. The best way to get this,
    is to show drive contents as a tree. There you can select
    and deselect files from different directories, any way you
    want. When ready, you select the @{" Add-Button " Link BUT2} and everything
    is put into an archive. In the same way, archive contents
    are displayed as a tree.
    More-over, I wanted to use PacShell to take a quick look
    into archives. It should be possible, to show their
    contents, read some files, and extract them, when wanted.
    For this reason, PacShell has a build in @{" File-Viewer " Link ViewWin}, which
    can display ASCII and binary files in HEX notation. Also it
    can display files directly out of an archive, if they are
    only stored or lh5-packed.

@Endnode



@Node PacFiles "Files, related to PacShell"
    The following files are released together with PacShell:

    PacShell			The Programm
    PacShell.cfg		The configuration file
    PacShell.guide		The German Documentation
    English Doc/PacShell.guide	The English Documentation
    LiesMich			German readme
    ReadMe			English readme

    This files must always be distributed together.
    See at: @{" Legal Stuff " Link "Rechtliches"}.

    In addition, a file called PacShell.dat is created by
    PacShell, when a Save-Button is used in one of the dialogs
    and it is NOT allowed to distribute this file.

@Endnode


@Node Requirements "System requirements"
    Software requirements
    PacShell needs AmigaOS 2.0 or higher to run. The AmigaGuide
    should also be installed, because it's needed for the
    Online-help.
    Because the amigaguide.library has some difficult problems,
    which cause to unfound nodes and even crashes, PacShell only
    accepts a version equal or higher than 34.
    In addition, you need the archivers for packing, unpacking
    and so on.

    Hardware requirements
    PacShell has not many or high hardware requirements. An
    68000 processor is fast enough and less than 200kB are used
    by PacShell itself. But you don't have to forget the
    requirements of the archivers you use with PacShell. But
    1MB should always be enogh.

    Stack size
    Much stack space is not needed and 4096 Bytes is always
    enough. In Version 1.02 or later, PacShell tests, if the
    stack is big enough and won't start, if it is smaller than
    4000 Bytes.
    The size of the stack for external programs can now be
    configured and is 10000 Bytes by default.

@Endnode


@Node Installation "Installation of PacShell"
    There is not much to install, if you want to use PacShell.
    You only need to copy or extract all files to a single
    directory. If you want to use the English documentation,
    you have to copy it into the same directory with PacShell
    and to overwrite the German documentation.

    For the configuration of basic things, there is a dialog in
    PacShell. You can open it by pressing the F6 key or by
    clicking in the 'Extra ...' button, which opens another
    dialog where you find a butten named 'Config'. Clicking this
    button also opens the configuration dialog.

@Endnode

@Node Features "Some Features of PacShell"
    * Supports archives of the formats Lharc/Lha, Lzx, Arc, Zoo,
	Zip, Rar, Arj, Tar and Diffy.

    * For each of this archive formats, PacShell has own reading
      algorithms.

    * Contents of Archives and Volumes are dislayed hierachical
      as a @{" tree " Link MainListBox}, so it is easy possible to select entries from
      different directories at the same time.

    * PacShell has, @{" configurable dialogs " Link DDL}, so that you can put
      the options that you need into a dialog.

    * As well controlable with the @{" keyboard " Link Keyboard} as with the mouse.

    * Dialogs and Windows are font sensitive and even
      proportional fonts are allowed.

    * Build in @{" Viewer " Link PacView} with ASCII and Hex display. External
      Viewers can be configured for a file extension.

    * The internal Viewer has it's own lh5-decoder, so that you
      can take a quick look into Lha/LHarc archives.

    * Context sensitive online help with AmigaGuide.

    * @{" Drag & Drop " Link DragDrop} of Files into archives is supported.

    * Many possibilities to select files.

    * Efficient usage of memory, dialogs are created for
      example, when they are opend the first time.

    * The @{" demo version " Link DemoVersion} is fully functional.

@Endnode


@Node Extensions "Possible Extensions"
    Some things, that PacShell perhaps will have in one of the
    next versions:

    * More archiv formats.

    * Other objekts in user configurable dialogs.

    * perhaps support for multi-volume-archivs.

    * ...

@Endnode


@Node Rechtliches "Legal Stuff"
    Use at your own risk
    --------------------
    All use of PacShell is made at your own risk. No warranty is
    made. The author cannot be made responsible for any damage
    that may be caused by the use of PacShell.

    Redistribution of PacShell
    --------------------------
    You may redistribute PacShell as an archive or unarchived,
    as long as all @{" files of PacShell " Link PacFiles} are distributed together.
    It is forbidden, to give away a .dat file that PacShell
    creates, in special, if it contains the registration code.
    All files must be redistributed in unchanged form as
    distributed by me.
    PacShell may only be redistributed for non-profit and it
    must be visible that PacShell is Shareware and the buyer of
    a disk is not be freed of paying the Shareware fee, if he
    uses PacShell.

    Shareware
    ---------
    PacShell is Shareware and if you uses it regularly, after a
    test period of 30 days you MUST @{" register " Link Register} for it.

@Endnode


@Node Register "Registration"
    PacShell is Shareware and if you use it regularly, you must
    register for it. Then you get a registration code, that must
    be entered together with your name. Until further notice,
    this code stays valid for future versions of PacShell.

    The registration fee is 30 DM or 25 US$.

    My Address:     Chrstian Wempe
		    St. Antoniort 28
		    49610 Quakenbrueck
		    Germany

    Please send bug reports, suggestions and so on also to this
    address.

    I currently don't own an E-Mail-Address, but who wants, can
    send his E-Mails to following address:

	Holger_Weets@OL.maus.de

    Holger will forward the mails to me.

@Endnode


@Node DemoVersion "Limitations in the unregistriered version"
    Even in demo mode PacShell is fully functional, there is no
    limitation of functionality.
    But the following things are different, when you have
    entered the correct registration key:

    * You are no longer asked, if you want to enter the
      registration code, every time you start PacShell.

    * The demo reminders, when calling an archiver or
      self-configured external tool, no longer apper.

    * PacShell terminates immediatly and not after first waiting
      15 seconds.

@Endnode


@Node ShortDesc "Quickstart"
    For those, who does'nt want to read the whole documentation,
    before trying out PacShell, I wrote this page and you should
    read it, to know about the most important things.

    PacShell comes with a ready-made configuration file, where
    all supported archivers are configured. That does not mean,
    that they are found on every system and eventually the
    pathes have to be altered. For this there is a @{" Dialog " Link ConfigDialog} in
    PacShell, that can be opened by pressing the F6 key or by
    selecting the [Config] button in the @{" Extra-Dialog " Link ExtraDialog}.
    By using the cycle-button there, you can select the archiver
    for which you want to enter the path. Every further use of
    this button accepts the changes. When finish select [Save]
    to save or [Use] to use the settings.

    After starting, you see a @{" listbox " Link MainListBox} with a list of the
    available volumes. By double-clicking on an entry you can
    open that drive. The contents are displayed as a tree, but
    at first only the top-most directory level. Double-clicking
    a directory opens it and inserts it into the tree. When you
    double-click on a file that is recognized as an archiv, this
    is opened an the contents are displayed in the listbox.
    Double-clicking on all other files, shows them in the
    viewer. PacShell has it's own @{" file viewer " Link ViewWin}, which can
    dislay ASCII files and also binary files in HEX mode. But
    it's also possible, to configure external tools for a class
    of files, which have the same suffix. File-viewing even
    works in archives, and when neccessary, PacShell extracts
    files temporary.

    The @{" path-field " Link PathGad} beneath the listbox contains the destination
    path that is used for several actions like extracting from
    archives. You can enter a path directly here or by clicking
    on a directory-entry in the listbox with simultaneously
    pressed Shift-key.
    The @{" archive-field " Link ArchiveGad} beneath the listbox contains the
    destination archiv that is used for several actions, like
    adding to an archive. Yor can enter an archive-name directly
    here or by clicking on an archive-entry in the listbox wuth
    simultaneously pressed Shift-key.

    When you have selected a destination archive, you can select
    as many entries in the listbox as you want and by clicking
    on the @{" Add-Button " Link BUT2}, they are put into this archive.
    When you have selected a destination path, you can selected
    as many entries from an archive in the listbox as you want
    and by clicking on the @{" Extract-Button " Link BUT1}, they are extracted
    from the archive.

    Of course, this is really not everything, you can do with
    PacShell. But here, that must be enough an if you want to
    know more, you have to read the whole documentation.

@Endnode


##
## Chapter 2	Windows and dialogs
##

@Node PacDials "PacShells windows and dialogs"
    This chapter decribes the dialogs in PacShell. Every dialog
    is described at least on one page and each of this pages can
    be displayed by pressing the help key, when the dialog is
    open and the AmigaGuide is installed. For this, it is also
    neccessary the the file PacShell.guide is placed in the same
    directory as PacShell or in the search-path-list of
    AmigaGuide.

@Endnode


@Node PacWin "The main window of PacShell"
The main window of PacShell looks something like this:
____________________________________________________________________________
|_|______________________________________________________________________|_|
| ________________________________________________________________________ |
| |								       | | |
| |								       | | |
| |								       | | |
| |								       | | |
| |								       | | |
| |			       @{" The Listbox " Link "MainListBox"}                           | | |
| |								       | | |
| |								       | | |
| |								       | | |
| |								       |_| |
| |								       |_| |
| |____________________________________________________________________|_| |
|	   ________________________		 _______________________   |
|  @{" Path " Link "PathGad"} |________________________|  @{" Archive " Link "ArchiveGad"} |_______________________|  |
|									   |
|  @{" Extract  " Link BUT1}@{"   Add    " Link BUT2}     @{"   Move   " Link BUT3}@{"  Update  " Link But4}@{" Freshen  " Link BUT5}     @{"  Delete  " Link BUT6}  |
|  @{"   Test   " Link BUT7}     @{"   Back   " Link BUT8}@{"   Root   " Link BUT9}     @{" Mark ... " Link BUT10}@{" Mark All " Link BUT11}@{"Unmark All" Link BUT12}  |
|  @{"   Help   " Link BUT13}     @{"  User 1  " Link UserButs}@{"  User 2  " Link UserButs}@{"  User 3  " Link UserButs}     @{"  Options " Link BUT17}@{"Extra ... " Link ExtraDialog}  |
|__________________________________________________________________________|

@Endnode


@Node MainListBox "The listbox in the main window"
    Here, the contents of archives and volumes are dislayed as
    tree. The main selection list, where you can select a volume
    or an already read archive, is also dislplayed here.

    In the main selection list, the following things are shown:
    Name	Name of a volume or an archive.
    Type	Volume or archive type (LHarc, Zip, ...)
    Date	Date of the entry.
    Time	Time of the entry.

    If the contents of a volume is dislayed, this things are
    shown:
    Name	Name of a file or directory
    Length	Length of a file or 'dir', if it is a directory
    Attrib	The file attributes
    Date	Date of the entry.
    Time	Time of the entry.

    If the contents of an archive are dislayed, this is shown:
    Name	Name of a file or directory
    Length	The uncompressed length of the file, or 'dir'
    Packed	The compressed length of a file
    Ratio	The compression ratio: The percentage of bytes
		the packed data is shorter than the original
		size. PacShell always uses this method and it
		can be different from that the archiver shows.
    Date	Date of the entry.
    Time	Time of the entry.

    The contents of a diffy archive are displayd as follows:
    Name	Name of a file or directory
    Code	The length of the code block
    Data	Number of bytes taken from the new file
    Total	Total bytes: code + data
    Date	Date of the entry.
    Time	Time of the entry.

    Mouse operation:
    A single click on an entry selects or deselects it. If the
    mouse is moved with the left key pushed down, the selection
    of the first entry is made to all other entries. If you
    reach the top or bottom border, the list is scrolled, if
    further possible.
    What happens on a double-click depends on the type of the
    entry. In the main selection list (Root), a double-click
    opens the volume or archive and dislays it in the listbox.
    Directories are always opened or closed. Archives in a
    volume-tree are opened and displayed in the listbox. All
    other entries are displayed with the internal or an external
    viewer, if such one is configured.
    A single click with pressed down Shift-key outside of an
    archive on a volume or directory copies the path into the
    path-field beneath the listbox.
    A single click with pressed down Shift-key outside of an
    archive, that has the extension of an archive, is copied
    into the archive-field beneath the listbox.

    Keyboard usage is described at @{" Keyboard control of listboxes " Link "ListBoxKeys"}

@Endnode


@Node PathGad "The input field for the destination path"
    This field must always contain a path. This is used as the
    destination path for archivr calls and extracted files are
    placed here. In configuration this path may be used with the
    @{" macro %p " Link "Makros"}. You should always finish your input with the
    return-key, because then PacShell tests, if the path exits
    and expands relative pathes to it's full length.

    A single click with pressed down Shift-key on an entry in
    the listbox, that is a directory or a volume also enters a
    path here.

    Furthermore, it is possible, to drag the icon of a volume or
    a directory from a workbench window onto this gadget.

@Endnode


@Node ArchiveGad "Das Eingabefeld für das ZielArchiv"
    This field must always contain the name of an archive. This
    is used as the destination archive for archiver calls and
    files are put into this archive. In configuration, this
    archive may be used with the @{" macro %a " Link "Makros"}. You should always
    finish your input with the return-key, because then PacShell
    tests, if the archive exits or can be created and expands
    relative pathes to it's full length.

    A single click with pressed down Shift-key on an entry in
    the listbox, that is an archive, also puts the name of that
    archive here.

    Furthermore, it is possible, to drag icons of an archive
    from a worbench window onto this gadget.

@Endnode


@Node BUT1 "The Extract Button"
    By pressing this button, the selected files, or all, if
    nothing is selected, are extracted from an opened archive.
    The destination path is the one, entered in the path field.

    This button is disabled, if extracting isn't possible, when
    no archive is opend or the corresponding archiver call is
    not configured for this archive type.

    If you hold down the Shift key, when you select this button,
    the call is made in background. But then, it is not possible
    to reread something.

    Relevant @{" arguments " Link CallList}: ArcName_Extract, ArcName_Extract1

@Endnode


@Node BUT2 "The Add Button"
    By pressing this button, the selected files are added to an
    archive. If nothing is selected, the volume name is passed
    to the archiver and everything is archived. The destination
    archive is the one, entered in the archive field.

    This button is disabled, if adding isn't possible, when an
    archive is displayed or the corresponding archiver call is
    not configured for this archive type.

    If you hold down the Shift key, when you select this button,
    the call is made in background. But then, it is not possible
    to reread something.

    Relevant @{" arguments " Link CallList}: ArcName_Add, ArcName_Add1

@Endnode


@Node BUT3 "The Move Button"
    By pressing this botton, selected files are moved into an
    archive. If nothing is selected, the volume name is passed
    to the archiver and everything is moved to into the archive.
    The destination archive is the one, entered in the archive
    field.

    This button is disabled, if moving isn't possible, when an
    archive is displayed or the corresponding archiver call
    isn't configured for that archive type.

    If you hold down the Shift key, when you select this button,
    the call is made in background. But then, it is not possible
    to reread something.

    Relevant @{" arguments " Link CallList}: ArcName_Move, ArcName_Move1

@Endnode


@Node BUT4 "The Update Button"
    Usually, with this button, the contents of an archive are
    updated, that means, old files are replaced by newer ones
    and files that don't exist in the archive, are added to it.
    The archivers usually have an update command for this.
    A few archivers (Zip, Lha) also can do this in the other
    direction, i.e. updating files on a drive.

    This button is disabled, if updating in the current
    direction isn't possible.

    If you hold down the Shift key, when you select this button,
    the call is made in background. But then, it is not possible
    to reread something.

    Relevant @{" arguments " Link CallList}: ArcName_Update, ArcName_Update1

@Endnode


@Node BUT5 "The Freshen Button"
    Usally, with this button, the contents of an archive are
    freshened, that means, old files are replaced by newer ones.
    The arichvers usually have a freshen command for this.
    A few archivers (Zip, Lha) also can do this in the other
    direction, i.e. freshening files on a drive.

    This button is disabled, if freshening in the current
    direction isn't possible.

    If you hold down the Shift key, when you select this button,
    the call is made in background. But then, it is not possible
    to reread something.

    Relevant @{" arguments " Link CallList}: ArcName_Freshen, ArcName_Freshen1

@Endnode


@Node BUT6 "The Delete Button"
    Depending on the displayed list/tree, selecting this button
    performs a deletition on the selected entries:

    In the main selection list:
    Removes archives from the list or cleares the cashes of
    volume trees. If a volume is no longer mounted, it is also
    removed from the list. No security-request is made here,
    because nothing is really (on the disk) deleted.

    In volume trees:
    The selected files and directories are deleted from the
    drive. Here, a security-request is made. Deleting is done
    recursive, with all contained subdirectories.

    In archives:
    The selected files are removed from the archive. A
    security-request is made and the archiver has do be
    configured for deletition or the button is disabled, if an
    archive is displayed.
    If you hold down the Shift key, when you select this button,
    the call is made in background. But then, it is not possible
    to reread something.

    Relevant @{" arguments " Link CallList}: ArcName_Delete, ArcName_Delete1

@Endnode


@Node BUT7 "The Test Button"
    With this button, the contents of an archive are tested. If
    an archive is displayed in the listbox, this is taken.
    Otherwise, the archive in the archive field, the destination
    archive, is taken. Selective testing is only possible, if
    the archiver can do it.

    With Diffy, the path field is also used. Here the old files
    are searched.

    This button is disabled, if no archiv can be determined or
    if the corresponding archiver call is not configured.

    If you hold down the Shift key, when you select this button,
    the call is made in background. But then, it is not possible
    to reread something.

    Relevant @{" arguments " Link CallList}: ArcName_Test, ArcName_Test1

@endnode


@Node BUT8 "The Back Button"
    With this button you can get back to the last displayed
    tree. For example, if you have opened an archive, you can
    get back to the directory, that contains it, if you press
    this button.
    This button is disabled, if a last dislpayed tree yet
    doesn't exist or if it has been deleted.

@Endnode


@Node BUT9 "The Root Button"
    With this button you can display the main selection list
    (the root list). It is disabled, if this list is currently
    displayed.

@endnode


@Node BUT10 "The Mark... Button"
    Clicking this button opens the dialog, where you can enter
    conditions for selecting files.
    See more at {" Selektion dialog " Link MarkDialog}

@Endnode


@Node BUT11 "The Mark All Button"
    After clicking this button, all entries in the list or tree
    are selected.

@Endnode


@Node BUT12 "Der Unmark All Knopf"
    After clicking this button, all entries in the list or tree
    are deselected.

@Endnode


@Node BUT13 "The Help Button"
    With this button, you can display the help for the main
    window. Pressing the help key has the same function.

@Endnode


@Node UserButs "The user-definable Buttons"
    PacShell has several user-definable buttons, as well in the
    main window as in the extra-dialog.
    As well the text in the button, as the commando that will be
    executed, can be @{" configured " Link UBConv}. If this command isn't
    configured, such a button is disabled.

    For demonstration purposes, the buttons in the main window
    are configured with the following standard AmigaDos
    commands:

    Touch	Sets the file date of all selected files.
		Uses SetDate.
    Copy	Copies selected files to the destination path.
		Uses Copy.
    NewShell	Opens a new shell. Uses NewShell

    If you hold down the Shift key, when you select this button,
    the call is made in background. But then, it is not possible
    to reread something.

    Relevant @{" arguments " Link CallList}: UserCall1, UserCall2, UserCall3, ...

@endnode


@Node BUT17 "The Options Button"
    With this button you can open the @{" option-dialog " Link "Optiondialogs"} for the
    corresponding archiver. If an archive is displayed in the
    listbox, this archive type is taken, otherwise that of the
    archive in the archive field. If you select this button with
    pressed down Shift-key, always the last mentioned is taken.

    This button is disabled, if no archive type is determinable
    or the corresponding dialog is not defined.

    Each of this dialogs is @{" configurable " Link DDL} and is defined in the
    file PacShell.cfg.

@Endnode


@Node ExtraDialog "The Extra Button"
    The Extra Button opens a dialog, where further functions can
    be selected:

    Edit Args
    Opens the @{" dialog " Link EditArgs}, where the argumentes
    can be edited within PacShell.
    This function can also be reached with the F2 key.

    UserDialog
    Opens a @{" dialog " Link UserDialog}, which is fully user-definable.
    This function can also be reached with the F5 key.

    Repack
    With clicking this button, you can convert on archiv to
    another format. The archiv displayed in the listbox is
    converted to the archiv given in the archive field. The
    corresponding archiver calls must be defined and the two
    archive formarts must be different or this button will be
    disabled.
    This function can also be reached with the F4 key.
    Relevant @{" arguments " Link CallList}: ArcName_ExtractAll, ArcName_AddAll

    Show All
    Shows the whole tree, i.e. all the contents of an archive or
    a volume. All directories are read in and displayed.
    This function can also be reached with the F3 key and is
    abortable with CTRL-C.

    Info
    Shows the obligatory about-dialog.
    This function can also be reached with the F1 key.

    Config
    Opens the @{" Dialog " Link "ConfigDialog"}, where the most important things
    can be configured.
    This function can also be reached with the F6 key.

    User4
    This is a @{" user-definable button " Link "UserButs"}
    This function can also be reached with the F9 key.

    User5
    This is also a  @{" user-definable button " Link "UserButs"}
    This function can also be reached with the F10 key.

@Endnode


@Node EditArgs "The dialog for editing of arguments"
    Within this dialog all the arguments, PacShell uses, can be
    edited. With this, PacShell can be configured in a wide
    range. Most of the arguments, PacShell knows, are related to
    calls of the several archivers. But also @{" user-buttons " Link UserButs} and
    internal things are configurable in this way.
    For this, read @{" Argument Overview " Link ArgList} and @{" Call Overview " Link CallList}.

    In the listbox of this dialog, all the arguments currently
    defined are listed. By double-clicking upon one of it, it is
    copied into the edit fields.
    @{" This listbox is controlable with the keyboard " Link "ListBoxKeys"}

    Name
    Here stands the name of the argument you want to edit.

    Value
    This is the value of that argument.

    Update
    If this button is selected, the argument edited is put into
    the list with it's (new) value. An already existing entry is
    overwritten by this. Changes are not applicable, until this
    button is selected.

    Remove
    With this button, the selected entry in the lisbox is
    removed from the list.

    Save
    Selecting this button saves the whole list of arguments and
    the dialog is closed.

    Use
    Closes the dialog without saving the arguments. Changes are
    effective, until you leave PacShell.

@Endnode


@Node ConfigDialog "The Configuration Dialog"
    This dialog is specific for doing a quick and easy basic
    configuration of PacShell. The most important arguments and
    variables can be configured here. Only the most important or
    often changed things are considered here:

    TempDir
    Here, a path can be given, where PacShell itself puts it's
    temporary files, for example, when a file is temporary
    extracted from an archiv.

    Default Path
    The path, that is written in the path field at program
    start. Changes are first effective at the next start of
    PacShell.

    Search Path
    The path list, where all programs, that are started by
    PacShell are searched. The specified directories must be
    separated by semicolons.

    Info-Mode
    Here you can select, how PacShell shall handle .info files.
    Changes are immediatly effective, but nothing is read in
    again.

    Edit Pathes for
    Here, the archive type can be selected, for which you want
    to edit the following pathes.

    Packer
    Name and Path of the archiver, that shall be is used for
    packing files. If the same archiver is used for packing and
    unpacking, the name is entered here.

    UnPacker
    Name and Path of the archiver, that shall be used to unpack
    files. If only an unpacker is available, e.g. UnRar, you
    must enter it's name here.

    More information at: @{" Configuration arguments " Link ArgList}

@Endnode


@Node UserDialog "The Dialog definable by the user"
    You can use this dialog in any way you want. The definition
    must be placed in the file PacShell.cfg.
    In this dialog can be placed settings for commands you put
    on the @{" user-buttons " Link "UserButs"}, even more commands and also buttons
    that open further dialogs.

    Note:
    If you write a help page for this dialog, you should put it
    into a seperate help file, because that it is not deleted,
    if you install a new version of PacShell.guide.

@Endnode


@Node ViewWin "The window for viewing files"
    PacShell contains a file viewer for displaying ASCII and
    binary files. If a file contains Null-bytes, it is displayed
    in HEX-format, else as an ASCII file.

    The Scrollbars and Arrow-buttons can be used as usual to
    scroll through the file.

    The following keys habe a function in this window:

    ESC 	    Closes the window and removes the file from
		    memory.

    CURSOR	    Scroll up or down one line or one charcter
		    to the left or right.

    SHIFT + CURSOR  One page up, down to the left or the right.

    ALT + CURSOR    Goto the beginning or the end of the file or
		    the line.

    HELP	    Shows this page, if AmigaGuide is installed.

    b		    Goto the end of the file.

    t		    Goto the beginning of the file.

    g		    Goto line. A dialog is opened, in which you
		    can enter the line number. If nothing is
		    entered, the operation is cancelled. The
		    destination line is displayed inverted.

    f		    Search for a string. A dialog is opened,
		    where you can enter the string. If nothing
		    is entered, the operation is cancelled.
		    If an occurrance is found, it is jumped to
		    this line, that will be displayed inverted.
		    If a file is dislplayed in HEX-notation, it
		    is also possible, to enter a HEX-code here.
		    This is recognized automatically.

    n		    Find next occurance an allready entered
		    string.

    p		    Find previois occurance of an allready
		    entered string.

    Note:
    The view-window is non-modal, that means, you can continue
    to work in the PacShell-window and even open further files
    for viewing. You can open as many files for viewing as you
    want, limited only by your main memory.

@Endnode


@Node MarkDialog "The Selektion dialog"
@Next StrDial
    Here you can enter several conditions, that are used to
    select or deselect files from the file list. All entered
    conditions must be true at the same time, and if one is
    false for a file, all following tests are skipped. If an
    entry is already selected (or deselected, if you want to
    deselect files), nothing is testet.


    File Type
    With this, you can choose the type of the entries. Possible
    selections are all entries (All), only files (Files) or only
    directories (Dirs).

    Archive Bit
    With this cycle-button, you can select, if the archive bit
    should be set, unset or ignored.

    Path
    Here, you can enter a path, where all matching entries must
    be located. They must be in this directory or one of it's
    subdirectories. You can also use this, when selecting files
    of an archive.
    The full path, but without the name of the volume must be
    entered here. Volume labels (everything before a :) is
    simply ignored.

    Pattern
    An @{" AmigaDos Pattern " Link DosPattern}, that the entries must match, can be
    entered here. If nothing is entered, this test is skipped.

    StartDate
    Here you can enter a date of the format dd-mm-yy. Giving a
    time is optional and must be of the format hh:mm. If no time
    is given, 0:00 is assumed. Files don't have to be older than
    this date/time.

    EndDate
    Here you can enter a date/time in the same way as at
    StartDate, but here 23:59 is assumed, if no time is given.
    Files don't have to be newer than this date/time.
    Together with StartDate you can specify a period in which
    the matched files must be created or modified.

    String, Offset
    Here you can enter a string, that will be searched inside of
    a file, upto the given offset. If no offset is given, it
    wholebe searchedin the whole file.
    There are some options for the search routine, that you can
    specify at the start of the string. These are introduced
    with a backslash ('\'):
    \b	    All characters, that have an ASCII code less than
	    the blank are converted to blank: Tab, newline,
	    carriage return, ...
    \c	    The search shall be case sensitive. By default it is
	    not.
    \m	    Convert multiple blanks into a single one. Together
	    with the option \b you can search whole sentences,
	    even if they are split to more than one line, in
	    this way.
    \\	    Backslash masks the backslash.
    Searching is only possible in files on a disk and otherwise
    this fields are disabled.

    Do inverted selection on unmatched entries
    This lets you select, what will happen to entries, that
    don't match at least one of the above conditions. If this
    flag is not selected, it stays as it was. Otherwise they are
    deselected, when seleting files or selected, when
    deselecting files.

    Select
    Does a selection with the above specified conditions and
    closes the dialog.

    Deselect
    Does a deselection with the above specified conditions and
    closes the dialog.

    Cancel
    Closes the dialog, without selection or deselecting
    anything.

@Endnode


@Node DosPattern "AmigaDos Pattern"
@Next DosPattern
@Prev DosPattern
    A short overview of the AmigaDos Pattern:

    ?	    exactly one character
    #	    any number of the following pattern.
    ~	    the complement of the following expression
    |	    Or: <p1>|<p2> = Either <p1> or <p2>
    %	    matches an empty string
    '       masks a character
    ()	    used for building groups: #?.(txt|doc)

    For a full description, please read your AmigaDos manual.

@Endnode


@Node StrDial "Entering Strings or Numbers"
@Prev MarkDialog
    This dialog allways appears, when a string or a number must
    be entered. Currently this is used in the viewer, when
    searching for a string or jumping to a line, or when using
    the @{" macro %s " Link "Makros"}.

    In the input field, you must enter the string or the number.
    Pressing return, confirms the input.

    The OK-button also confirms the input.

    With the Cancel-button you can cancel the input.

@Endnode


@Node RegisterDialog "Eingabe des Registrierungscodes"
    Here you must enter your name and the registration key, that
    depends on your name. If you enter your name, you should
    take care of the correct spelling of your name, because the
    case is not ignored. With the key, this is not important.

    If you have entered the name an the code, you can save it to
    PacShell.dat by selecting the Save-button. Select Cancel, if
    you want don't want to save it.

    If the key is correct and matches the name, the demo-
    limitations are removed, otherwise everything stays as it
    was. You will get no message, if the code was correct or
    incorrect.

@Endnode


@Node Optiondialogs "Optionen-dialogs for Archivers"
    All the dialogs for editing options that are passed to the
    archivers, can be configured with a
    @{" dialog description language " Link DDL}, so everyone can use the options
    he needs.
    When you select the @{" Options button " Link BUT17} in the main window, the
    dialog of the corresponding archiver is opened.

    @{" LhA Options Dialog      " Link "LHarcOptsDialog"}           @{" Zip Options Dialog " Link "ZipOptsDialog"}
    @{" Diffy Options Dialog    " Link "DiffyOptsDialog"}           @{" Lzx Options Dialog " Link "LzxOptsDialog"}
    @{" (Un)Rar Options Dialog  " Link "RarOptsDialog"}

    The description here is made for the dialogs and archivers,
    that are configured by default. If you reconfigure them, you
    have to write your own documentation.

@Endnode


@Node LHarcOptsDialog "Options of LhA"
    Options of Lha, used when adding files to archives:

    Collect files recursively  (-r)
    Recursive scanning and archiving of all subdirectories of
    the speciefied directories.

    Archive empty directories  (-e)
    Empty directories shall be put into the archive, when they
    are inside of an archived directory.

    Archive with pathnames  (-x)
    Put names with full pathes into the archive.

    Compression Speed  (-z -v0 -v5 -v9)
    Here you can select, if LhA shall pack files faster or more
    efficient or if files shall only be stored.

    Don't preserve attributes  (-a0)
    The current attributes of a file are put into the archive.

    Use archive-bit  (-s)
    Uses the archive bit and adds only those files, which have
    it not set.

    Set archive-bit after adding  (-S)
    Sets the archive bit after adding a file to the archive.
    Very usefull with the previous mentioned option.

    Kill empty directories (Move)  (-K)
    When you are moving files into an archive, it can happen
    that empty directories remain on the disk. With this option
    they are removed afterwards.

    Options of Lha, used when extracting files from archives:

    Extract without pathnames  (-x0)
    Files shall be extracted, ignoring their path and are placed
    directly in the destination directory. Note: Some versions
    of LhA can't to this, if a name is specified with a path,
    but PacShell must do this.

    Touch extracted files  (-E)
    Extracted files are touched, their file date is set to the
    current date/time afer ectracting.

    Preserve attributes  (-a)
    The file attributes are set to that from the archive. Don't
    use, if they come from a different platform.

    Don't clear archive-bit  (-C0)
    Archive bit of extracted files shall not be cleared.

    General options:

    Quiet mode	(-q)
    LhA is quiet and makes no output.

    Disable interactivity  (-m)
    Lha makes no questions

    Ignore filenotes  -f
    Filenotes are ignored and neither archived, nor extracted.

    Make filenames lowercase  (-l)
    Filenames are converted to lowercase. Usefull, if extracting
    files from an archive, created under MS-Dos.

    Work Directory  (-w)
    The working directory, LhA uses for it's temporary files.

    See also: @{" LhA Documentation " Link "LhA.man/MAIN"}

@Endnode


@Node LzxOptsDialog "Optionen of Lzx"
    Options of Lzx, used when adding files to archives:

    Collect files recursively  (-r)
    Recursive scanning and archiving of all subdirectories of
    the speciefied directories.

    Archive empty directories  (-e)
    Empty directories shall be put into the archive, when they
    are inside of an archived directory.

    Archive with pathnames  (-x)
    Put names with full pathes into the archive.

    Compression Speed  (-0 -1 -2 -3 -9)
    Here you can select how good or fast lzx compresses files.

    Don't preserve attributes  (-a0)
    The current attributes of a file are put into the archive.

    Use archive-bit  (-s)
    Uses the archive bit and adds only those files, which have
    it not set.

    Set archive-bit after adding  (-S)
    Sets the archive bit after adding a file to the archive.
    Very usefull with the previous mentioned option.

    Options of Lzx, used when extracting files from archives:

    Extract without pathnames  (-x0)
    Files shall be extracted with full path name.

    Touch extracted files  (-E)
    Extracted files are touched, their file date is set to the
    current date/time afer ectracting.

    Preserve attributes  (-a)
    Ignore attributes from archives and don't set them.

    Don't clear archive-bit  (-C0)
    Archive bit of extracted files shall not be cleared.

    Other options of Lzx, used where applicable:

    Quiet mode	(-q)
    LhA is quiet and makes no output.

    Disable interactivity  (-m)
    Lha makes no questions

    Ignore filenotes  -f
    Filenotes are ignored and neither archived, nor extracted.

    Make filenames lowercase  (-l)
    Filenames are converted to lowercase. Usefull, if extracting
    files from an archive, created under MS-Dos.

    Merge group size  ("-M")
    Maximum size in kB, that Lzx uses to merge files into one
    block.

    Work Directory  (-w)
    The working directory, LhA uses for it's temporary files.

    See also: @{" Lzx Documentation " Link "Lzx.guide/MAIN"}

@Endnode


@Node ZipOptsDialog "Optionen of Zip / UnZip"
    Short desecription of the options available here:

    ZIP Options:

    Collect files recursively  (-r)
    Recursive scanning and archiving of all subdirectories of
    the speciefied directories.

    Archive without pathnames  (-j)
    Ignore pathnames, even if specified, and archive only the
    filename.

    Allow growing existing zipfile  (-g)
    Allows Zip to let grow an existing zipfile. May be
    dangerous, if an error occurs.

    Quiet mode	(-q)
    Zip is quiet and makes no output.

    Simulate PKZIP made zipfile  (-k)
    For compatibility with PKZIP: Convers pathnames to MS-Dos
    pathnames, uses only MS-Dos attributes and marks the entry
    as made under MS-Dos.

    Encrypt (verify key)  (-ee)
    Encrypt the files. The key is asked twice, the second time
    for verification.

    Speed  (-0 -1 -5 -9)
    Here you can selected the compression speed of zip. The
    fastest is 'store', where nothing is compressed.

    Work Directory  (-b)
    Working directory, where zip puts it's temporary files.

    UNZIP Optionen:

    Extract without pathnames  (-j)
    Files shall be extracted without pathname and are placed
    directly in the destination directory.

    Never overwrite existing files  (-n)
    Unzip never extracts a file, when there is one with the same
    name in the destination directory.

    Overwrite without prompting  (-o)
    The opposite of the previos option, Unzip overwrites files,
    without asking.

    Quiet mode	(-q)
    UnZip is quiet and makes no output.

    Convert text (CR LF => LF)	(-a)
    Converts the CR LF combination used under MS-Dos to LF, used
    under AmigaDos for indicating the end of a line.

    Don't make names lowercase  (-U)
    Filenames shall not be converted to lowercase, if the entry
    was made under MS-Dos.

    See also: @{" Zip Documentation   " Link "zip.doc/MAIN"}
	      @{" UnZip Documentation " Link "unzip.doc/MAIN"}

@Endnode


@Node DiffyOptsDialog "Options of Diffy"
    Short desecription of the options available here:

    Don't collect files recursively  (-r)
    Diffy, by default, scans directories recursively. With this
    option you can surpress it.

    Archive with pathnames  (-x)
    Put names with full pathes into the archive.

    Don't swap, if new file is older  (-c)
    If two files compared, and the file expected to be the new
    one is older, diffy swaps the old and new file. If you don't
    want that, use this option.

    Add new files  (-n)
    New files, that do not exist in the directory with the old
    files are put entirely into the archive.

    Archive obsolete files  (-e)
    Obsolete files, only existing in the directory with old
    files, are marked in the archive, that they can be deleted.

    Use old (short) Headers  (-h)
    Tells diffy to use it's old and shorter headers.

    Block size	(-b0 bis -b9)
    Controls the size of blocks in the new file, diffy searches
    in the entire old file.

    Quiet mode	(-qq)
    Diffy shall be quiet, really no message is made.

    Note:
    Diffy is configured in a way, that the path field is used as
    the place where old files are searched.

    See also: @{" Diffy Documentation " Link "Diffy.guide/MAIN"}

@Endnode


@Node RarOptsDialog "Option of UnRar"
    UnRar has only one option, that can be used here, namely if
    to extract with or without the pathname.

    Siehe auch: @{" UnRar Documentation " Link "UnRar_Amiga.doc/MAIN"}

@Endnode


##
## Chapter 3	    Configuration
##

@Node Configuration "The Configuration of PacShell"
    PacShell is configurable in many ways. Thus you are not
    forced to use a special archiver for an archive format and
    if there are more than one, e.g. for lharc, you can use the
    one that you prefer most. It is even possible, to use
    different programs for ectracting, adding and so on.
    But it should be possible, to set options within dialogs and
    therefore PacShell has a @{" dialog description language " Link DDL}.
    Moreover, several other things are configurable, like
    user-buttons, applications for a suffix, and some internal
    things. This is explained on the following pages.

    Many things have been configured by me for a default
    configuration and therefore it is not necessary to learn
    about PacShell's configuration.

    In this documentation, it is more or less the standard
    configuration that is explained. But if you want, you're
    able to make your own and very different configuration.

@Endnode


@Node ComConv "Configuring Archivers and other commands"
    The central point of PacShell really is the configuration of
    archivers and other commands, because that is, what PacShell
    has to do: Calling them with the right parameters.

    Whenever an external program is executed, the corresponding
    definition of the call is serched in the list of arguments.
    Then, this argument is expanded, where formal parameters
    (variables and macros) are replaced with their actual
    values. Moreover, several paramters for PacShell itself are
    evaluated.
    In this way, a command line is created, that is executed.
    This can get very long, when there are many selcted files,
    that must be inserted. There is no limitation in length
    here.

    An example:
    Set "Zip_Extract"   "[cdj]UnZip -x $Unzip_Opts %l %w"

    Or general:
    Set "call_name"     "[Options]command definition"

    The names of the calls are predefined. See at
    @{" List of Calls " Link CallList} .

    The first thing in a command definition, between the [ and
    the ] are the @{" options for PacShell " Link "PacOpts"}.
    If no options are specified, the brackets can also be left
    out. Then follows the definition of the command, that can
    include @{" variables " Link CommVars} (with $) and @{" macros " Link Makros} (with %).

@Endnode


@Node CallList "List of call-names"
    1. Names of the archiver-calls
    ------------------------------
    The names of the archiver-calls are put together from the
    name of the archiver and the action that is performed. These
    two words are parted by an underscore. The names of the
    archivers are Arc, Arj, Diffy, LHArc, Lzx, Rar, Tar, Zip and
    Zoo.
    The names of the actions are: Add, Add1, Add2, Extract,
    Extract1, Move, Move1, Update, Update1, Freshen, Freshen1,
    Delete, Delete1, Test, Test1, ExtractTemp, ExtractAll und
    AddAll.
    The simple names (without a number at the end) are used,
    when an archiv is currently displayed.
    The names with a 1 at the end are used, when the contents of
    a volume are displayed.
    Add2 is used, when files are are dragged from a worbench
    window onto PacShells window, when an archiv is displayed.
    ExtractTemp is used, when a file is extracted temporary.
    ExtractAll and AddAll are used, when Repack is selected
    (converting from one archive format to another).
    The name of the argument used, when selected files are added
    to a zip-archive, therefore is Zip_Add1.
    In addition there is an argument for every archiver called
    arcname_MatchAll, that must be defined with a pattern that
    the archiver can use to match all files, e.g. * or #?.

    2. Names of the freely definable buttons
    ----------------------------------------
    UserCall1, UserCall2, UserCall3, UserCall4, UserCall5

    3. Names of viewer-applications
    -------------------------------
    The name of the argument, bound to the suffix .xyz is .xyz

@Endnode


@Node PacOpts "Optionen for PacShell in Commands"
    At the beginning of a command definition, the options for
    PacShell are specified. They must be enclosed in []
    brackets. Example:
	Set "Zip_Extract" "[cdj]UnZip -x %l %w"

    The optionen are:

    a	When expanding a command, by default, PacShell quotes
	all filenames, if they could contain blanks. If this
	causes a problem, you can use this option to surpress
	it.

    b	This option is a workaround for some versions of Lha,
	that cannot extract files without path, if a filename is
	passed with the pathname to it. When PacShell extracts
	files temporary with the help of an archiver, it is
	neccessary that they're extracted without path. Because
	it is possible, that there are files with the same name
	and a different path in an archive, the name should be
	passed with it's pathname. But for this versions of Lha
	this does'nt work and with this option you can tell
	PacShell, to specify only the filename. This option
	affects the @{" macro %t " Link Makros}, when used with @{" LhA_ExtractTemp " Link CallList},
	but can be used everywhere, where such problems occur.

    c	With this option you tell PacShell to close it's console
	window, after executing this command. If this option is
	left out, you have to close the window ny yourself.

    d	If this option is specified, the current directory is
	set to that entered in the path field, before the
	command is executed. This option is for example used,
	when an archiver does'nt accept the destination path as
	a parameter and always extracts to the current
	directory.

    j	This options tells PacShell, that it must reread a
	special directory after executing a command. This can be
	the path of the opened volume, the one entered in the
	path field or the current directory. This is dependend
	on the last expanded macro or on the option d.

    k	With this option you tell PacShell to reread the
	directory, where the archive is, if that may be changed
	by executing this command.

    l	This options tells PacShell to reread the contents of
	the archive, that is changed by the command.

    n	When this option is specified, PacShell will not open a
	console window for the command. You won't see any
	output, when PacShell is started from worbench, but if
	it is run out of a Shell, the output goes to the
	shell-window.

    p	Prints the expandet command. This option was built in
	for testing the configuration of archivers.

    r	The execution of the command is repeated until an error
	occurs or the macro %n (get next selected entry) no
	longer can be expanded. When you use this option and
	this macro together, the command is executed once for
	every selected entry.

    w	Tells PacShell to wait until the return key is pressed,
	when it executes a tool in a parallel task. In this
	case, PacShell has to close the console window, before
	the task is terminated. When a file is double-clicked,
	PacShell may execute a command in such a parallel task
	and when you define it, you can use this option if it is
	neccessary.

    If a command is executed in a parallel task, i.e. when
    double-clicking in a file, the options j, k, l and r are not
    usable and are ignored. The option w only then is usable.

@Endnode


@Node CommVars "Inserting Variables into Calls"
    Variables can be inserted into commands, that are executed
    by PacShell, by inserting them with a preceeding $ sign.
    If the name of the variable contains blanks, it may be
    quoted. When the definition is written into the
    configuration file, the definition itself is a string and
    therefore, this qotes must be masked with a backslash.
    Examples:
	"search $Variable -x -y -z"
	"search $\"Eine Variable\" -x -y -z"

    Variables that can be used here, are all that are declared
    with @{" Var " Link Var}, @{" LocalVar " Link LocalVar} and @{" EnvVar " Link EnvVar} and also every global
    environment variable.

    In the definition of the archiver-calls, the names of the
    archivers itself are specified as a variable, because it's
    an easy way to change the path at only one place in the
    configuration file and furthermore, this variables can be
    edited within PacShell.

@Endnode


@Node Makros "Makros in Kommandoaufrufen"
    The most important thing, concerning the expansion of
    commands are macros. These are expandet to actual parametes
    like filenames, pathes and so on. All macros are specified
    as a single character with a preceeding % sign. Example:

	Set "Zip_Extract" "[cdj]UnZip -x  %l %w"

    The following macros are availabe:

    a	The name of the archive, that has been entered in the
	archive field. If there is nothing entered, the
	expansion fails.

    d	The name of the configurable temporary directory, that
	PacShell uses. Default: "T:"

    f	When this macro is expanded, a fileselector is called
	and the selected filename is inserted into the command.
	If no file is selected, the expansion fails. A title for
	the fileselector can be given in brackets:
	%f(select file)

    l	Name of the archive that is displayed in the listbox. If
	no archive is displayed there, the expansion fails.

    n	Name of the next selected entry. If no or no more entry
	is selected, the expansion fails. This can be used
	together with @{" option r " Link PacOpts}.

    p	The path entered in the path field. If nothing is
	entered there, the expansion fails.

    q	The name of the volume displayed in the listbox. If
	somethong other is displayed there, the expansion fails.

    s	Opens a small dialog, where you can enter a string. If
	nothing is entered or Cancel is selected, the expansion
	fails. Otherwise, the entered string is inserted into
	the command. As with the fileselector, a title can be
	given in brackets: %s(Search for)

    t	This is a temporary name, specifing the name of the
	file, which has been double-clicked. If this comes from
	an archive, it has been temporary extracted.

    v	This is a list-macro, i.e. a macro that can be expanded
	to more than one filename. This macro is replaced with
	the list of files, that have been selected on a volume.
	If nothing is selected, it expands to the name of the
	volume. This macro also sets the current directory to
	the lowest one, that is a parent of all selected files.
	Filenames then are created relative to this path. This
	macro overrides the @{" option d " Link PacOpts}.

    w	This is another list-macro and it is replaced with all
	files that are selected in an archive. If nothing is
	selected, it is expanded to an empty string, but the
	expansion continues.
	All filenames are created with their full pathnames.

    x	The third list-macro, that is replaced with a group of
	filenames, that have been dragged onto PacShells window.
	All of this files are in the same directory and for
	files in differen direcories, PacShell executes the
	command arcname_add2 more than one time.
	Filenames are created without path and the contents of a
	directory passed here is created with the name of this.

    It is only allowed, to use one of the list-macros v, w and x
    at the same time or the expansion is terminated with an
    error-message.
    The list-macros can be expanded to an unknown length and
    PacShell has no limitation here and reallocates the used
    buffer, if this is neccessary.

@Endnode


@Node AppAssign "Assigning Applications to File-extensions"
    With use of the file-extension, it is possible, to assign an
    application to a type of files. If such a file is
    double-clicked then, this application is executed with with
    the file as parameter.
    To define such an aplication, you only need to define an
    argument, that has the name of the file-extension including
    the point.
    Applications defined in this way are always executed in a
    seperate task, so that more than one file can be viewed at
    the same time. The task is created by PacShell and deletes
    at it's end the temporary file, that is created, when a file
    is viewed out of an archive.
    Example:

	SET ".gif" "ViewGif %t"

    This statement means, that PacShell shall try to execute a
    tool named ViewGif, whenever a file with the extension .gif
    is double-clicked.

    If an application shall be assigned to more than one file
    type, it must be specified for each of it:

	SET ".gif" "ViewPicture %t"
	SET ".jpg" "ViewPicture %t"

    Changes and new entries in the @{" Argument-Edit-Dialog " Link EditArgs} are
    immediatly available.

    Of course, an application don't has to be a viewer and in
    this way, tools like gzip or uudecode can be configured.
    The extension .run for example is configured to execute the
    double-clicked file itself:

	SET ".run"   "[d]%t"

@Endnode


@Node UBConv "Configuring User-buttons"
    The configurable buttons in the main window and in the Extra
    dialog are configured in this way:

    For each button there are two arguments: UserXText and
    UserCallX. E.g. for the first button that are User1Text and
    UserCall1.
    With UserXText you can specify a text up to 10 characters
    that is placed in the button.
    With UserCallX you can define the command that is executed,
    when the button is selected.

    Examples:

    SET "User1Text" "_Copy"
    SET "UserCall1" "[cj]Copy FROM %v TO %p ALL QUIET CLONE"

    Changes and new entries in the @{" Argument-Edit-Dialog " Link EditArgs} are
    available at the next start of PacShell.

@Endnode


@Node UDConv "Den User Dialog konfigurieren"
    The freely definable User-Dialog can be defined like every
    other definable dialog, using the
    @{" dialog-description-language " Link DDL}.
    It is only important, that it's name is UserDialog.

@Endnode


@Node DDL "The Dialog-Description-Language"
    PacShell supports a language, that can be used to define
    dialogs like the option dialogs for archivers or a freely
    usable dialog. This is a very simple language and PacShell
    calculates as much as possible by itself. The basic
    configuration is also done with this language.

    @{" General notes about the language " Link LangGComm}

    @{" The concept of variables and objects " Link VarConcept}

    @{" The layout of dialogs " Link DialogLayout}

    The keywords:

    @{" Dialog " Link Dialog}             @{" End " Link End}

    @{" PushButton " Link Pushbutton}         @{" CheckBox " Link Checkbox}          @{" StringField " Link Stringfield}
    @{" CycleButton " Link CycleButton}        @{" Border " Link Border}             @{" Text " Link Text}
    @{" Color " Link Color}

    @{" Console " Link Console}            @{" Guide " Link Guide}             @{" LocalVar " Link LocalVar}
    @{" Var " Link Var}                @{" EnvVar " Link EnvVar}            @{" Set " Link Set}

    @{" Comments " Link Comments}

@Endnode


@Node LangGComm " General notes about the language "
    Some importand things, you have to know, if you use this
    language to define a dialog:

    1. There is no line structure, i.e. the text is read
       character by character. Newlines are handled like blanks.

    2. The writing of keywords is case-insensitive, so it is
       the same, if you write DIALOG, dialog or DiALoG.

    3. There are three different token types: keywords, strings
       and numbers. Strings must be enclosed in double-qoutes
       (") and quotes inside a string must be masked with a
       backslash. The same must be done with the backslash
       itself. All tokens beginning with a decimal number (0..9)
       are interpreted as a number. Only decimal numbers are
       allowed. All other tokens are interpreted as keywords.

    4. When the first error occurs, the interpretation is
       cancelled and PacShell terminates with an error message.

@Endnode


@Node VarConcept "The concept of variables and objects"
    Within PacShell, variables are used, to pass options to
    external commands. Currently you can use two kinds of
    objects to edit variables inside dialogs. These are
    @{" input-fields " Link StringField} and @{" checkboxes " Link CheckBox}.
    One variable can be used to hold the values of more than one
    of this objects and these must be seperated by blanks.
    If a checkbox is used, the string defined there is directly
    copied into the variable.
    If an input-field is used, the string defined there is used
    as a prefix, that preceeds the entered text.

    Example:   Search PATTERN xyz ALL

    This can be a simple command, that searches a string in
    files. The search-string is preceeded by a PATTERN keyword
    and ALL is an option for the search command.
    This two values shall be editable in a dialog and for this,
    you need two objects, an input-field and a checkbox:

    Dialog "Search" "Suchen in Dateien"
	Var "Search_Opts"
	Stringfield "Search for Pattern:" 0 0 20 64 "PATTERN "
	Checkbox "Search in Subdirectories" 0 2 "ALL"
	PushButton "Okay" 0 4 OK
	PushButton "Cancel" 20 4 CANCEL
    End

    This definition creates a dialog with the two objects and
    the result is put into the variable Search_Opts. In
    addition, there are two buttons, OK and Cancel.

    If the dialog is executed, and you enter 'Hallo' into the
    input-field, then the variable Search_Opts contains the
    string "PATTERN Hallo ALL".

    There are three types of variables: @{" local " Link LocalVar}, @{" global " Link Var} and
    @{" environment-variables " Link EnvVar}, which are different in the way,
    values are saved.
    Values of local variables are never saved.
    The values of global variables are saved to the file
    PacShell.dat
    Environment-variables are saved in ENV:, if an OK-button is
    selected, and in addition, in ENVARC:, if a Save-button is
    selected.

@Endnode


@Node DialogLayout "The Layout of Dialogs"
    As you see at the @{" Dialog command " Link Dialog}, you only need to specify
    the name and the title for a dialog. The size and position
    is calculated by PacShell. The height is determined from the
    object, that is nearest to the bottom and the width is
    determined from the object, which has the greatest extend to
    the right.
    All dialogs are centered on the screen, when they are opened
    the first time. If you move them, the new position is
    remembered, even if the dialog is closed.

    The position of all objects is NOT given in pixels, instead
    the size of the font is used.
    This means, that the dialog is rastered with the font-height
    and the extend of the widest character of the font.
    If you specify the position of an object, it is the number
    of such a rectangle, that you specify.
    If an objects needs the space of more than one rectangle, it
    is centered in a group of rectangles. For example, the
    space, that is used by a @{" PushButton " Link PushButton} is two rectangles in
    height and eleven in width.

    You should take care, that the dialog don't gets too big,
    because than it cannot be opened.

@Endnode


@Node "Dialog" "Dialog: Start of a dialog definition"
    SYNTAX
	    Dialog <Name> <Titel>

    PARAMETERS

    <name>  The name of the dialog. Some names are specific to
	    the @{" option dialogs " Link Optiondialogs} and the @{" user dialog " Link UserDialog}, and others
	    are freely choosable for the SHOW action at
	    @{" Pushbuttons " Link PushButton}.

    <titel> The title of the dialog, that is dislplayed in the
	    title line of the dialog.

    DESCRIPTION

    This keyword starts the definition of a dialog an everything
    between this keyword and the follwing @{" END " Link End} keyword is
    belonging to that dialog. The maximum number of dialogs you
    can define is 20. If you define more, the execution is
    terminated with an error message.


    EXAMPLE

	    Dialog "Zoo" "Optionen für Zoo"
		...
	    End

    SEE ALSO: @{" End " Link End} @{" Dialog Layout " Link DialogLayout}

@Endnode


@Node "End" "End: end of a dialog definition"
    SYNTAX
	    End

    DESCRIPTION

    This keyword indicates the end of a dialog definition, that
    has been started with @{" Dialog " Link Dialog}.

    EXAMPLE

	    Dialog "Main" "Optionens for XY"
		...
	    End

    SEE ALSO: @{" Dialog " Link Dialog}

@Endnode


@Node "PushButton" "PushButton: Definition of a Pushbutton"
    SYNTAX

	    PushButton <Text> <x> <y> <Action>

	    <Aktion> ::= Save | Ok | Cancel | Help |
			 Show <Dialogname> |
			 System <Kommandostring> [SAVE] [QUIT]

    PARAMETERS

    <Text>   The text that is displayed inside the botton. It
	     can be upto 10 characters long and is centered
	     inside the object.

    <x>      Horizontal position inside the dialog, specified in
	     character heights.

    <y>      Vertikal position inside the dialog, specified in
	     character widthes.

    <Action> One of the above mentioned actions, that is
	     performed, when the button is selected. See more at
	     @{" description of actions " Link Actions}.

    DESCRIPTION

    This instruction creates a pushbutton, that performs an
    actions, if it is clicked. The created object is centered in
    a raster of 2 charcters in height and 11 in width.
    This instruction can only be used between @{" Dialog " Link Dialog} and @{" End " Link End}.

    EXAMPLES

    PushButton "Help"  0  10 HELP             Display Help
    PushButton "More"  12 10 SHOW "Dialog2"   Open dialog
    PushButton "List"  12 10 SYSTEM "List"    execute tool

    SEE ALSO: @{" Description of actions " Link Actions}

@Endnode


@Node "CheckBox" "CheckBox: Definition of a Checkbox"
    SYNTAX

	    CheckBox <Text> <x> <y> <Str>

    PARAMETERS

    <Text>  The text of the object, placed behind the checkbox.

    <x>     Horizontal position inside the dialog, specified in
	    character heights.

    <y>     Vertikal position inside the dialog, specified in
	    character widthes.

    <Str>   The string, that will be inserted in the variable,
	    if the object is selected. (See @{" Concept " Link VarConcept})

    DESCRIPTION

    This instruction creates a checkbox, an object that can be
    either selected or deselected. It is centered in a raster of
    2 characters in heigth and (length of <Text> + 3) characters
    in width.
    This instruction can only be used between @{" Dialog " Link Dialog} and @{" End " Link End}.
    A variable must already been defined, before you use this
    instruction.

    EXAMPLE

	    CheckBox "No messages" 0 4 "-q"

    SEE ALSO: @{" LocalVar " Link LocalVar} @{" Var " Link Var} @{" EnvVar " Link "EnvVar"}

@Endnode


@Node "StringField" "StringField: Definition of an Input-field"
    SYNTAX

	    StringField <Text> <x> <y> <Width> <Size> <Str> [Flags]

    PARAMETERS

    <Text>  The text, that is placed either in front of the
	    object or above it, depending on [Flags]

    <x>     Horizontal position inside the dialog, specified in
	    character heights.

    <y>     Vertikal position inside the dialog, specified in
	    character widthes.

    <Width> The width of the object, i.e. the number of visible
	    characters in it.

    <Size>  Maximum number of characters, that can be entered
	    here. The maximal possible value is 255.

    <Str>   This is the string, that is used as a prefix for the
	    entered text, when it is inserted in the variable.
	    See: See @{" Concept " Link VarConcept}

    [Flags] Possible flags for this object:
	    TEXTTOP  The title is placed above the input-field.
	    CENTER   The entered text is centered inside the
		     object.
	    LONGINT  Only numbers can be entered

    DESCRIPTION

    This instruction creates a stringfield, where a text or a
    number can be entered. This object has a height of 2
    characters, if the text is placed in front of it, otherwise
    it has a height of 3 characters. The width of the object is
    (width + 3) characters, if text is placed above, otherwise
    it is (width + 3 + length of text).
    This instruction can only be used between @{" Dialog " Link Dialog} and @{" End " Link End}.
    A variable must already been defined, before you use this
    instruction.

    EXAMPLES

	    StringField "Errorfile" 0 0 30 100 "-e "
	    StringField "Search string" 0 0 20 100 "SEARCH " TEXTTOP
	    StringField "Number" 0 0 8 8 "-n" LONGINT CENTER

    SEE ALSO: @{" LocalVar " Link LocalVar} @{" Var " Link Var} @{" EnvVar " Link "EnvVar"}

@Endnode


@Node "CycleButton" "CycleButton: Definition of an Cyclebutton"
    SYNTAX

	    CycleButton <Text> <x> <y>
		    <str1> <vstr1>
		    <str2> <vstr2>
		    ...
		    <strN> <vstrN>
	    End

    PARAMETERS

    <Text>  The text, that is placed in front of the button

    <x>     Horizontal position inside the dialog, specified in
	    character heights.

    <y>     Vertikal position inside the dialog, specified in
	    character widthes.

    <strX>  One of the strings that are placed inside of the
	    button.

    <vstrX> The string belonging to <strX>, which is written
	    into the variable, when this is selected.

    DESCRIPTION

    With this instruction you can create a cycle-button inside
    of a dialog. With such a button exactly one string can be
    selected, that is written into the variable. This can be an
    empty string, which then is taken as default value.
    This object needs two characters in height and
    length(Text) + max(length(str1), ..., length(strN), 7) + 5
    characters in width.
    This instruction can only be used between @{" Dialog " Link Dialog} and @{" End " Link End}.
    A variable must already been defined, before you use this
    instruction.


    EXAMPLE

	    CycleButton "Compression Speed" 0 8
		    "Store"     "-0"
		    "Slow"      "-1"
		    "Average"   ""
		    "Fast"      "-9"
	    End

    SEE ALSO: @{" End " Link End} @{" LocalVar " Link LocalVar} @{" Var " Link Var} @{" EnvVar " Link "EnvVar"}

@Endnode


@Node "Console" "Console: Define a Console Window"
    SYNTAX

	    Console <Name>

    PARAMETERS

    <Name>  The (file-) name of the console, that is opened for
	    messages of the executed programs.

    DESCRIPTION

    With this instruction, you can choose, where the output of
    executed programs goes to. In general, this will be a
    console window, but it can also be a file or something else.
    This instruction can only be used once in the whole
    configuration.

    EXAMPLES

	Console "Con:20/20/400/100/Output/AUTO/CLOSE/SIMPLE"
	Console "Speak:"
	Console "S:PacShell.log"

    SEE ALSO: @{" Actions " Link Actions} and AmigaDos manual.

@Endnode


@Node "Guide" "Guide: Specifies Guide and Node"
    SYNTAX

	    Guide <guide> <node>

    PARAMETERS

    <guide> Name of a file in AmigaGuide format, that includes a
	    help page for this dialog.

    <node>  Name of the node within this file, which shall be
	    displayed at first, when help is called.

    DESCRIPTION

    With this instruction, you can select a help page, that is
    displayed, when the help key is used.
    This instruction can only be used between @{" Dialog " Link Dialog} and @{" End " Link End}.

    EXAMPLE

	    GUIDE "MyHelp.guide" "Zip Dialog"

    SEE ALSO: @{" Dialog " Link Dialog} @{" End " Link End} @{" Actions " Link Actions}

@Endnode


@Node "Var" "Var: Defines a global Variable"
    SYNTAX

	    Var <name> [<defau>]

    PARAMETER

    <name>  Name of a global variable.

    <defau> Default value, that is assigned to the variable, if
	    it is not already saved in PacShell.dat. This
	    parameter is optional.

    DESCRIPTION

    With this instruction, you select a variable, where the
    values of the objects are read from and written in.
    This declaration is valid for all following objects, until
    another @{" Var " Link Var}, @{" LocalVar " Link LocalVar} or @{" EnvVar " Link EnvVar} keyword is found.
    The values of variables, declared with this keyword are
    saved into the file PacShell.dat.
    You can define as many global variables as you want and they
    don't have to be editible with objects. But all global
    variables must be declared with this keyword, or they will
    be interpreted as an environment variable.

    EXAMPLE

	    Var "prog_opts" "-q -v -OT:tempfile"

    SEE ALSO: @{" CheckBox " Link Checkbox} @{" StringField " Link Stringfield} @{" Actions " Link Actions}

@Endnode


@Node "LocalVar" "LocalVar: Defines a local Variable"
    SYNTAX

	    LocalVar <name> [<defau>]

    PARAMETER

    <name>  Name of an internal variable.

    <defau> The value, that is assigned to the variable. This
	    parameter is optional.

    DESCRIPTION

    This instuction declares an internal variable, that objects
    use for their values. The difference between these and other
    variables is, that these are never saved.
    This declaration is valid for all following objects, until
    another @{" Var " Link Var}, @{" LocalVar " Link LocalVar} or @{" EnvVar " Link EnvVar} keyword is found.
    You can define as many lokal variables as you want and they
    don't have to be editible with objects. But all lokal
    variables must be declared with this keyword, or they will
    be interpreted as an environment variable.

    EXAMPLE

	    LocalVar "prog_opts" "-q -v -OT:tempfile"

    SEE ALSO: @{" CheckBox " Link Checkbox} @{" StringField " Link Stringfield} @{" Actions " Link Actions}

@Endnode


@Node "EnvVar" "EnvVar: Defines an Environment Variable"
    SYNTAX

	    EnvVar <name> [<defau>]


    PARAMETERS

    <name>  Name of a global environment variable

    <defau> Optional value, that is assigned to this variable.
	    It is ignored, if the variable already exits in your
	    environment.

    BESCHREIBUNG

    With this instruction you can use and edit global
    environment variables. These are read out at program start,
    an when OK is selected in a dialog, they are written back to
    ENV:, when SAVE is selected they're also written to ENVARC:
    This declaration is valid for all following objects, until
    another @{" Var " Link Var}, @{" LocalVar " Link LocalVar} or @{" EnvVar " Link EnvVar} keyword is found.

    EXAMPLE:

	    EnvVar "prog_opts" "-q -v -OT:tempfile"

    SEE ALSO: @{" CheckBox " Link Checkbox} @{" StringField " Link Stringfield} @{" Actions " Link Actions}

@Endnode


@Node "Set" "Set: Setting Arguments"
    SYNTAX

	    Set <name> <value>

    PARAMETERS

    <name>  Name of the arguments, that is defined.

    <value> Value of this argument.

    DESCRIPTION

    PacShell uses arguments, where it is neccessary to get
    things configurable, e.g. for archiver-calls.
    This arguments can be defined with this keyword and it is
    used, to do the standard configuration.
    If arguments are changed in PacShell, they are saved to
    PacShell.dat and this definitions overwrite those in the
    config-file.

    EXAMPLES

	Set "DisplayMode" "Simple"
	Set "Zip_Extract" "[cdj]$UnZip -x $Unzip_Opts %l %w"
	Set ".guide" "Sys:Utilities/amigaguide %t"

    SEE ALSOE: @{" Arguments of PacShell " Link ArgList} @{" List of Calls " Link CallList}

@Endnode


@Node Border "Border: Draw a Border inside a Dialog"
    SYNTAX

	    Border <text> <x> <y> <w> <h>

    PARAMETERS

    <text>  A string that is placed in the top of the border.

    <x>     Horizontal position inside the dialog, specified in
	    character heights.

    <y>     Vertikal position inside the dialog, specified in
	    character widthes.

    <w>     The width in character widthes of the font.

    <h>     The height in character heights of the font.

    DESCRIPTION

    This instruction can be used, to draw a border inside of a
    dialog. A text can be inserted in the top line of this
    border, so you can group objects and give them a title. The
    color of the text can be choosen with the color instruction.

    EXAMPLE

	    Border "Attribute" 0 4 20 10


    SEE ALSO: @{" Color " Link Color}

@Endnode


@Node Text "Text: Draw a Border inside a Dialog"
    SYNTAX

	    Text <text> <x> <y>

    PARAMETERS

    <text>  The string that shall be written into the dialog

    <x>     Horizontal position inside the dialog, specified in
	    character heights.

    <y>     Vertikal position inside the dialog, specified in
	    character widthes.

    DESCRIPTION

    With this instruction you can write texts into dialogs. The
    color of the text can be choosen with the color instruction.

    EXAMPLE

	    Text "This is a text" 0 0

    SEE ALSO: @{" Color " Link Color}

@Endnode


@Node Color "Color: Choose Text Color"
    SYNTAX

	    Color <nr>

    PARAMETER

    <nr>    The number of the color, you want to select

    DESCRIPTION

    With this instruction, you can choose the color of the
    texts, that are written with the @{" Text " Link Text} and or the @{" Border " Link Border}
    instruction. It is valid, until a new color is choosen and
    the default value is 2.

    EXAMPLE

	    Color 1

    SEE ALSO: @{" Border " Link Border} @{" Text " Link Text}

@Endnode


@Node Comments "Comments"
    The character # is used for comments. A comment starts with
    this character and ends at the end of the line:

    DIALOG "Hallo" "A Dialog"
    # This is a comment
    # and this also
    CHECKBOX "no messages" 0 0 "-q"      # the first objects
    ...

@Endnode


@Node Actions "Description of the Actions"
@Toc "Sprache"

    The following actions can be used with PushButtons:

    OK
    Accept all changes, made in a dialog. Closes the dialog an
    writes environment variables to ENV:.

    CANCEL
    Closes the dialog and discards changes.

    SAVE
    Saves all variables, that are used in this dialog, even
    those, that are not changed. Environment variables are
    written to ENVARC:, global variables to PacShell.dat

    HELP
    Display the help page for this dialog. It must be defined
    with the @{" Guide " Link Guide} keyword.

    SHOW <Dialogname>
    Opens the dialog, which has the name <Dialogname>.

    SYSTEM <commandstring> [SAVE] [QUIT]
    Does a system call with <commandstring>. The flag SAVE
    means, that all variables are saved, before the command is
    executed and should be used, if the command reads
    environment variables that are used here.
    If you specify the QUIT flag, the dialog is closed, before
    the command is executed.

@Endnode


@Node ArgList "Configuration arguments (Overview)"
    Many settings in PacShell can be configured with arguments,
    either in PacShell.cfg or with the Argument-Editing-Dialog.

    DefaultPath
    This path is written in the @{" path field " Link "PathGad"}, when PacShell is
    started.

    MaxHeight
    The maximum number of lines, that are displayed in the
    listbox inside the main window. With this, you can change
    the height of PacShell's window. If this argument is missed,
    as many lines as possible are displayed.

    TempDir
    A temporary directory, that is used by PacShell. Here,
    files, that are temporary extracted for viewing are placed,
    for example.

    TarTimeFix
    This is a fix for a version of a GNU tar, that I have
    testet. If the argument is defined, the fix is used, but
    it's value is not relevant. See: @{" Problems " Link Problems}

    Stack
    Stack size for programs that are called by PacShell. Default
    value is 10000 Bytes.

    Path
    The Search path list, a list of directories, separated by
    semicolons, where external programs are searched.

    DisplayMode
    Here you can select, how PacShell will handle .info files.
    Three settings are available:
    SIMPLE	(Default) All files are displayed, those with
		suffix .info, too. This is like that, what you
		see in a Shell.
    AUTOINFO	If a file has a corresponding .info file, that
		with the .info suffix is removed from the
		display. If there is only the file with .info at
		the end, then it is displayed with it's suffix.
    WORKBENCH	This is nearly the same as you see in a worbench
		window, when it displays all files. You will
		never see a file with the suffix .info.
    If you have choosen one of the last two modes, all .info
    files are handled internally and even passed to archivers,
    if a file is selected, which has a .info file.

    Examples:
    SET "DefaultPath" "Ram Disk:"
    SET "MaxHeight" "20"
    SET "TempDir" "sys:tmp/"
    SET "DisplayMode" "AutoInfo"

@Endnode


##
## Chapter 4	Working with PacShell
##

@Node PacUse "Working with PacShell"
    In this chapter, it is explained, how you can work with
    PacShell. Start point is the task you want to perform and
    then it is explained, how you can do this.

@Endnode


@Node PacStart "Starting PacShell"
    PacShell can be started either out of a Shell or from the
    workbench. In both cases, you can pass one archive as
    parameter, that will be opened and displayed.

    Starting PacShell out of a Shell
    Usage: PacShell [ArchivName]
    This starts PacShell, opens the archive and displays it.
    Even if the current directory is not that of PacShell,
    PacShell finds the files PacShell.cfg and PacShell.dat. So
    it is not possible, to use different versions of these
    files. But the advantage is, that PacShell will always find
    this files.

    Starting PacShell from Workbench
    PacShell can be started from workbench as usual, with a
    double-click on it's icon. Only the firts argument passed is
    used, the others are ignored. This way, you can open
    archives, by selecting PacShell's icon and then
    double-clicking on an archive with pressed down shift key.
    Also, it is possible to use PacShell as default tool for
    archives.

@Endnode


@Node DragDrop "Drag & Drop"
    It is possible, to drag files from a workbench window onto
    PacShell's window. How PacShell handles this, depends on
    where the files are dropped:

    An object, that you drop over the @{" archive field " Link ArchiveGad}, and that is
    known as archive, is entered there.

    An icon, that represents a volume or a directory and is
    dropped over the @{" path field " Link PathGad}, is entered there.

    If an archive is dragged upon the @{" listbox " Link MainListBox} in the main
    window, it will be read in and displayed there.

    If an archive is displayed in the listbox of the main
    window, you can drag files onto it and that will be added to
    the archive. Files are added without pathname and the files
    of an directory are added with the name of the directory.

    If no archive is displayed and you drag an directory or
    volume icon onto it, this directory will be displayed.

@Endnode


@Node Keyboard "Using the keyboard"
    PacShell can be fully contolled with the keyboard. All
    buttons have a hotkey, which is underlined in most cases.
    Cancel buttons can be used with the ESC key, because this
    closes the window and this has the same function.
    @{" Using the keyboard in listboxes " Link ListBoxKeys}, see next page.

@Endnode


@Node ListBoxKeys "Keyboard control of listboxes"
    All listboxes (currently 2) can be controlled with the
    following keys:

    CursorUp / CursorDown
    Moves the cursor one line up or down

    Shift-CursorUp / Shift-CursorDown
    One page up or one page down

    CTRL-CursorUp / CTRL-CursorDown
    Scrolling up or down, without moving the cursor

    Shift-CTRL-CursorUp / Shift-CTRL-CursorDown
    Jumps to th previous / next selected line
    (only in listboxes, where more than one line can be selected)

    Alt-CursorUp / Alt-Cursor-Down
    Jumps to the first or last line.

    Leertaste
    Toggles the selection of the current line and, if more than
    one line can be selected, the cursor is moved down one line.

    Return
    This has the same function as a double-click on this line.

    Shift-Return
    This has the same function as a single click with pressed
    down shift key.

@Endnode


@Node ExtractDemo "Extracting from archives with PacShell"
    Files are extracted from an archive with PacShell in the
    following way:

    1. Selected a destination path. It must be entered in the
       @{" path field " Link PathGad} by either dragging an icon onto it, clicking
       on a directory with pressed down shift key or by writing
       it into this field.

    2. Now you can open the archive, where you want to extract
       the files from. If there are pathes in the archive, they
       first are displayed folded and by double-clicking them,
       they can be unfolded like other directories. Or you can
       press F3 and everything is unfolded.

    3. When you have opened all directories, that contain files,
       you want to extract, you can begin to select the files.
       That can be done with the keyboard (spacebar), with the
       mouse (single click) or with conditions entered in the
       @{" Mark-Dialog " Link MarkDialog}.

    4. Now select the @{" Extract Button " Link BUT1} and PacShell starts the
       archiver to extract the files.

    When the extracting is done, PacShell rereads the
    destination path and displays it.

@Endnode


@Node ArchivDemo "Archiving with PacShell"
    Files are added to an new or existing archive with PacShell
    in the following way:

    1. select a destination archive. It must be entered in the
       @{" archive field " Link ArchiveGad} by either dragging an archive onto it,
       clicking on an archive in the listbox with pressed down
       shift key, or by writing it into this field.

    2. Now you can open one volume and there open all the
       directories, which contain files that you want to
       archive.

    3. Now you can select the files, with the mouse, the
       keyboard or with the @{" Mark-Dialog " Link MarkDialog}.
       If you want to add a special part of the path to the
       archive, select the directories of this path, too.
       PacShell creates pathes from that point, that contains
       all selected entries.

    4. Now select the @{" Add Button " Link BUT2} (or alternatively move, update
       or freshen) and PacShell runs the archiver.

    After the archiving, PacShell rereads the contents of the
    archive and displays it.

    It is also possible, to archive files with @{" Drag & Drop " Link DragDrop}.

@Endnode


@Node DiffyUse "Usage of Diffy"
    Diffy is has many differences to the other supported
    archivers, because it needs a reference directory for
    packing (diff) and unpacking (patch), where old files are
    searched.

    When patching, the difference is not so great. It is only
    important, that the old files must be found in the
    destination path. Then, you can patch files there from an
    opened archive.
    Moreover, I decided to use the @{" Update Button " Link BUT4} for the patch
    action, because I found that more intuitive.

    When you create a new diff-archive, the difference is much
    greater, because even then the directory entered in the path
    field is used.

@Endnode


@Node PacView "Viewing files with PacShell"
    With a double-click on a file in the lisbox, a file can be
    viewed. This can be files from a directory or from an
    archive, that are temporary extracted.
    Usually, the internal viewer is used, which can display
    ASCII files and binary files in HEX notation. But it is also
    possible to @{" configure an external viewer " Link AppAssign} for a special file
    extension.
    The internal viewer can read files directly out of an
    archive, if they are only stored or packed with lh5 in an
    lharc-archive.

@Endnode


@Node GetHelp "Hilfe aufrufen"
    You can use the help key in PacShell at any time. Then,
    PacShell calls the AmigaGuide to display a help page which
    belongs to the current active window. This works with all
    windows of PacShell, except the console window opened for
    external commands.

    The file PacShell.guide should be in the same directory with
    PacShell, that it can be found.

@Endnode


@Node QuitPacShell "Quitting PacShell"
    PacShell can be quietted by clicking on the close button in
    the @{" main window " Link PacWin} or by pressing the ESC key, when this window
    is active.
    All other opened windows and dialogs are close, before
    PacShell quits.
    There is no request, if you really want to quit PacShell,
    because you cannot loose any important data.

    In demo-mode PacShell waits 15 seconds until it really quits
    and during this time the window of PacShell is held active
    and in the foreground. This time left is indicated by a
    flashing text in the info-line.

@Endnode


##
## Chapter 5	Kwon extensions
##

@Node ArcSuffixes "Known File Extensions"
    The following file extensions are recognized by PacShell and
    assigned to the following archive types:

    Extension			Archive type
    ---------			------------
    .arc			Arc
    .arj			Arj
    .dfy			Diffy
    .lzh und .lha		LHarc, LhA
    .lzx			Lzx
    .rar			Rar
    .tar			Tar
    .zip			Zip
    .zoo			Zoo

@Endnode


##
## Chapter 6	Problems
##

@Node Problems "Problems with Archivers"
    The following problems occured, when I tested this
    archivers:

    Arc V0.23
    ---------
    I have only found a very old version of Arc for the Amiga,
    and I don't know, if there is a newer one. This version
    isn't able, to archive or extract files with pathnames. But
    from other systems, there may be arc-archives, that contain
    pathes and PacShell can read them.

    Arj (UnArj 2.41)
    ----------------
    Only an UnArj is available and this even cannot extract
    files selective. So it is only possible, to extract all
    files at once from an arj-archive.

    Diffy V2.00
    -----------
    There are no problems, because I wrote diffy and had the
    possibilty to fix all problems there. But it's not really an
    archiver and some things are a little bit different.

    LhA V1.32
    ---------
    This version of LhA isn't able to extract files without
    pathname, if they're passed with pathname. To avoid
    comlications with files that have the same filename but a
    different pathname, PacShell always specifies the full path
    and that means, you cannot extract files directly to the
    destination directory, if they have a path.
    When files are extracted temorarily for viewing, they need
    to be extracted without path and for this, there is an
    option, that PacShell shall only specify the filename. But
    this doesn't work correctly, if there are two files with the
    same filename.

    Lzx V1.21 EC
    ------------
    When Lzx merges files, it is not possible to determine the
    compressed length of a file merged together with others. The
    way Lzx shows the total uncompressed and total compressed
    length of a block is not possible within PacShell.
    In addition, the lzx support is very new in PacShell and I
    had no documentation about the archive format. Currently,
    the reading of an lzx archive is aborted, whenever something
    unexpected is found in a header. But with this version of
    Lzx it never happend.

    Rar (Unrar 1.02)
    ----------------
    You can only extract from rar-archives, but this works
    without problems.

    Tar (GNU Tar V.??)
    ------------------
    The version of gnutar, I tested, seems to hava a very
    strange date-time-format. It stores the number of seconds
    since 1.1.78. In the usual Unix format of date/time, it
    should be the seconds since 1.1.70. With an argument, you
    can choose, which format PacShell shall use, but there can
    always be archives, where wrong dates are shown.

    Zoo V2.00
    ---------
    The way options are passed to Zoo, makes it impossible to
    edit them in a dialog. But there aren't many options and zoo
    isn't often used today. For this reason I don't added
    support for this option format.

    Zip (InfoZip Zip V2.0.1, UnZip V5.12)
    -------------------------------------
    Ignores the rest of the command line, if it gets too long.

@Endnode

##
## Chapter 7	    What's new?
##

@Node Changes "Neues in dieser Version"
    Version 1.04
    ------------
    * Fixed many small bugs, mainly dislpay errors, when
      proportional fonts were used.

    Version 1.03
    ------------
    * After extracting, directories are now always read in and
      not only, if they were already read. So the destinantion
      directory is always displayed, when something was
      extracted.

    Version 1.02
    ------------
    * At start, it is tested, if stack size is at least 4000
      Bytes.

    * I have completely rewritten the way PacShell calls
      external programs, so that it is possible to pass very
      long command lines.

    * New arguments: Path, Stack

    Version 1.01
    ------------
    * It is now possible, to make archiver calls in background,
      when you hold down the Shift key, when you select a button
      like the Add button.

    * In the viewer, now line numbers and total lines are
      displayed in the window title.

    * The mouse pointer is now changed to a wait pointer in some
      places.

    * You can now use cycle-buttons in definable dialogs

    Version 1.00
    ------------
    This is the first version, but in future, here you can read,
    what's new in PacShell.

@Endnode


